[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"can i use scrapecreators.com to do scrape youtube comments if i give a google sheet of urls Yes—if ScrapeCreators supports a “bulk YouTube comments” task that accepts a Google Sheet/CSV of video URLs (or video IDs). But there are two big caveats you should verify before you build a workflow: Compliance risk: scraping YouTube HTML (vs using the official YouTube Data API) can violate YouTube Terms and get blocked/rate-limited. Practical fit: some tools say “Google Sheets input” but really mean “upload CSV” or “paste list,” and many require video IDs (not full URLs). Below is a non-coder, click-by-click SOP to confirm capability and set up a reliable workflow, plus a safer alternative if ScrapeCreators isn’t API-based. Knowledge Base (KB) — Chat Thread: “YouTube Comments via ScrapeCreators + Google Sheet” KB v1.0 (2025-12-22) Goal: Bulk pull YouTube comments from a list of video URLs in Google Sheets. Decisions to confirm: Does ScrapeCreators use YouTube Data API or web scraping? Does it accept Google Sheets URL, CSV upload, or paste list? Required input: video URL vs video ID Output fields needed: comment text, author, likes, timestamp, reply count, etc. Primary risks: ToS compliance, rate limits, missing comments (pagination, disabled comments), data quality. Core assets to create: a standardized Google Sheet template; extraction settings; output schema; QA checks. 1) The Straight Answer: Can you do it? Potentially yes, if ScrapeCreators has: A YouTube comments extractor, AND A “bulk input” option that can ingest a Google Sheet of URLs (or you can export sheet → CSV and upload), AND It can map each row to a YouTube video (URL or ID). Because I can’t verify ScrapeCreators’ current product features from here, the next section is the fastest verification workflow. 2) Fast Verification SOP (10–15 minutes) Click-by-click SOP (with expected inputs/outputs) Step\tAction (Click-by-click)\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tWhy this step matters 1\tOpen ScrapeCreators → Find “YouTube” category → look for “YouTube Comments”\tNone\tYou see a specific extractor/workflow for comments\tConfirms the tool actually supports comments (not just channel/video metadata) 2\tClick the YouTube Comments tool → check “Input” section\tYour test video URL\tIt clearly states accepted formats: URL / ID / playlist / channel\tPrevents building the wrong sheet format 3\tLook for “Bulk” options: “Upload CSV”, “Paste list”, “Google Sheets”, “Webhook”, “API”\tA small list of 3–5 URLs\tA bulk input method is available\tConfirms this can scale beyond one-off extraction 4\tIf “Google Sheets” is supported: paste the published Google Sheet link (view access)\tGoogle Sheet share link\tTool accepts sheet and previews rows\tConfirms direct sheet ingestion works 5\tIf Sheets isn’t supported: export Google Sheet → File → Download → CSV → upload CSV\tCSV file\tTool accepts CSV and maps column\tMost tools work via CSV even if they mention Sheets loosely 6\tConfigure extraction settings: max comments per video, include replies, sort order\tExample: 300 comments/video, include replies=Yes\tSettings saved\tControls data volume and relevance 7\tRun a test job on 1–2 videos\t1–2 URLs\tOutput preview/download appears\tValidates you’ll get the fields you need 8\tDownload output (CSV/JSON/Sheet)\tNone\tOutput file with comment rows\tConfirms your pipeline works end-to-end 9\tQA check: verify counts and missing cases\tCompare YouTube visible comment count vs exported\tYou identify gaps/limits\tPrevents false confidence in “complete” data 10\tScale up to full sheet\tYour full URL list\tCompleted export\tNow you’re operational 3) Build the Right Google Sheet (Template + URL → Video ID) Many comment tools work more reliably with video IDs. Here’s a sheet structure you can use immediately. Recommended Sheet Columns Column\tExample\tNotes video_url\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ\tYour source list video_id\tdQw4w9WgXcQ\tOften required for APIs/tools label\t“Competitor A – Launch Video”\tHelps segmentation notes\t“Pull top comments + replies”\tInternal context Google Sheets formulas (no code) Extract video ID from common URL formats Put this in B2 (video_id), assuming URL in A2: Copy =IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"v=([^&]+)\"), IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"youtu\\.be/([^?&]+)\"), IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"shorts/([^?&]+)\"), \"\"))) Expected output: the 11-character YouTube video ID. 4) Important: ToS + Risk Reality Check What you should confirm about ScrapeCreators If it uses the official YouTube Data API: generally safer and more stable. If it scrapes page HTML: higher risk of breaking/blocks and potential ToS issues. Practical limits regardless of tool Some videos have comments disabled “Top comments” vs “Newest first” can change what you see Replies may require extra pagination Large pulls can hit rate limits or quotas 5) Safer Alternative (If You Want Lowest-Risk) If ScrapeCreators can’t do it cleanly, the most compliant approach is YouTube Data API through a no-code connector (examples: Make/Zapier + a YouTube module, or a Sheets connector that supports YouTube API). This typically requires: A Google Cloud project Enabling YouTube Data API v3 OAuth / API key handling (click-by-click doable) If you want, I can give you a full click-by-click SOP for that route too. 6) “Interactive” Flowchart (Process Map) Yes No No Yes Google Sheet: video URLs Tool accepts Google Sheets directly? Paste Sheet share link into ScrapeCreators Export Sheet to CSV Upload CSV to ScrapeCreators Configure: max comments, include replies, sort Run test on 1-2 videos Output matches needs? Adjust settings / switch to video IDs / change tool Run full batch Download CSV/JSON QA + Tagging + Analysis Copy 7) What I need from you to give a definitive answer (2 minutes) Reply with: A screenshot of the ScrapeCreators “YouTube comments” page (inputs + export options), or paste the relevant text from their docs Your desired output fields (minimum: comment text + author + date + like count?) Rough scale: how many videos and max comments per video? Then I’ll update the KB with: The exact sheet format ScrapeCreators expects The exact run settings A QA checklist A conversion-focused way to turn comment insights into product angles, ads, and content briefs (without ToS headaches) Sources (for compliance + constraints) YouTube Data API v3 documentation: https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3 YouTube API Services Terms of Service: https://developers.google.com/youtube/terms/api-services-terms-of-service YouTube Terms of Service: https://www.youtube.com/t/terms If you paste your Sheet URL list format (just 5 sample rows, no private data) and what ScrapeCreators is showing for “input,” I’ll tell you exactly whether it’ll work and the cleanest setup. https://docs.scrapecreators.com/v/youtube/video/comments i want the content of the video comments ranked by most liked comments into a google sheet along with the meteics of rhe respective video.  if i give a google sheet of youtube videos You can do this with ScrapeCreators as long as you accept one key reality: YouTube does not natively offer “sort by most liked” as an API order option (it offers relevance or time). So the reliable method is: extract comments (preferably “top/relevance” + enough volume) → then sort/rank by likeCount inside Google Sheets. Source: YouTube Data API commentThreads.list supports order=time|relevance, not likeCount. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/commentThreads/list Below is a click-by-click SOP to (1) feed ScrapeCreators a Google Sheet of YouTube videos, (2) export comments + video metrics, and (3) rank comments by most liked in Google Sheets. KB (Knowledge Base) — “ScrapeCreators YouTube Comments → Google Sheets” KB v1.1 (2025-12-22) Goal: From a Google Sheet of YouTube video URLs, pull video metrics + comments, then rank comments by likeCount and deliver into Google Sheets. Constraints: API ordering does not sort by likeCount; must sort post-extraction in Sheets. Primary Entities: Video list input (URLs + derived video IDs) Video metrics output (views, likes, commentCount, etc.) Comment rows output (text, author, likeCount, publishedAt, reply count, etc.) Join key: videoId 1) Sheet Setup (Input) — No-code, robust 1A) Create your input Google Sheet Tab name: INPUT_videos Column\tHeader\tExample\tExpected Output A\tvideo_url\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQw4w9WgXcQ\tRaw URLs you provide B\tvideo_id\tdQw4w9WgXcQ\tExtracted ID used by tools/APIs C\tlabel\tCompetitorA_Launch\tOptional segmentation Formula (B2) to extract video_id from common URL formats: Copy =IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"v=([^&]+)\"), IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"youtu\\.be/([^?&]+)\"), IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"shorts/([^?&]+)\"), \"\"))) Fill down. 1B) Make the sheet accessible to ScrapeCreators Click Share (top right) Set access to Anyone with the link: Viewer (or whichever level ScrapeCreators requires) Copy the share link Expected output: a shareable Google Sheet URL that ScrapeCreators can read. 2) ScrapeCreators Workflow (Comments + Video Metrics) You want two exports: Comments export (one row per comment/reply) Video metrics export (one row per video) Reason: comments endpoints typically don’t include the full set of video statistics; joining two clean tables in Sheets is faster and more reliable. 2A) Export YouTube Comments from your Sheet Use your docs page: https://docs.scrapecreators.com/v/youtube/video/comments SOP (click-by-click) — Comments job Step\tWhere to click\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tRationale 1\tScrapeCreators → YouTube → Video → Comments\tNone\tComments extractor page opens\tCorrect extractor 2\tFind Input section → choose Google Sheets (or “Bulk / Sheet”)\tGoogle Sheet share link\tTool accepts sheet as source\tEnables batch processing 3\tMap the column to use\tvideo_id (preferred) or video_url\tTool shows mapping / preview\tIDs reduce URL-format failures 4\tSet comment retrieval options\tOrder: Relevance/Top (if available), include replies Yes/No, max comments per video\tSaved settings\t“Relevance” approximates top comments; we’ll still sort by likeCount later 5\tRun a small test\t2–3 video IDs\tPreview / sample output rows\tValidates columns include likeCount and text 6\tRun full job\tFull sheet range\tCompleted run + export option\tProduces the dataset 7\tExport destination\tExport to Google Sheets (or CSV download)\tA new sheet/tab with comments\tYou get rows you can sort/rank What to confirm in the output columns (must-have): videoId commentId textDisplay or textOriginal (comment content) likeCount (this enables “most liked” ranking) publishedAt authorDisplayName (optional but useful) Reply metadata (if you included replies) Data support / fact-check: likeCount is a standard field for comment threads/items in YouTube API responses. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/commentThreads 2B) Export Video Metrics for those same videos In ScrapeCreators, look for a YouTube endpoint like Video Details, Video Stats, or Video Info (often maps to videos.list). SOP (click-by-click) — Video metrics job Step\tWhere to click\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tRationale 1\tScrapeCreators → YouTube → Video Details/Info/Stats\tNone\tVideo details extractor opens\tNeeded for per-video metrics 2\tInput source\tSame Google Sheet link\tTool reads video_id list\tKeeps keys consistent 3\tSelect fields/parts (if configurable)\tstatistics, snippet, contentDetails\tOutput includes views/likes/comments, title, date, duration\tEnsures you get metrics you asked for 4\tRun\tFull list\tOne row per video with metrics\tClean join table 5\tExport\tExport to Google Sheets\tA metrics tab/sheet\tReady to XLOOKUP into comments Metrics you likely want (tell me if you want others): title, channelTitle, publishedAt viewCount, likeCount, commentCount duration (optional), tags (optional) Source: YouTube videos.list provides statistics incl. view/like/comment counts. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/videos 3) Google Sheets: Join + Rank Comments by “Most Liked” Assume ScrapeCreators created two tabs: EXPORT_comments EXPORT_video_metrics 3A) Create a “FINAL_comments_ranked” tab Add these columns (example schema): Column\tHeader\tExpected Input\tExpected Output A\tvideoId\tfrom EXPORT_comments\tJoin key B\tvideoTitle\tXLOOKUP from metrics\tVideo title per comment C\tviewCount\tXLOOKUP from metrics\tVideo views per comment D\tcommentText\tfrom comments export\tThe content you want E\tcommentLikeCount\tfrom comments export\tThe rank metric F\tcommentPublishedAt\tfrom comments export\tTimestamp G\trankWithinVideo\tformula\t1 = most liked within that video XLOOKUP examples (adjust column letters to match your exports) Video title next to each comment: Copy =XLOOKUP(A2, EXPORT_video_metrics!A:A, EXPORT_video_metrics!B:B, \"\") (Where EXPORT_video_metrics!A:A = videoId, B:B = title) View count next to each comment: Copy =XLOOKUP(A2, EXPORT_video_metrics!A:A, EXPORT_video_metrics!C:C, \"\") 3B) Rank comments “most liked” within each video If your commentLikeCount is in column E and videoId in A: Copy =IF(A2=\"\",\"\",RANK.EQ(E2, FILTER($E:$E, $A:$A=A2), 0)) Expected output: rank 1 = highest liked comment for that video. 3C) Create a “Top N comments per video” view In a new tab TOP10_per_video, put a videoId in A2, then: Copy =LET( vid, $A2, rows, FILTER(FINAL_comments_ranked!A:G, FINAL_comments_ranked!A:A=vid), SORT(rows, 5, FALSE) ) That sorts rows for that video by commentLikeCount descending (column 5 in the A:G range). 4) Process Flow (interactive diagram) Syntax error in text mermaid version 11.12.0 Copy 5) Two quick clarifying questions (so I can lock your exact SOP to your exports) In ScrapeCreators’ Video → Comments output, do you see a field named exactly likeCount (or similar)? If you paste 1 sample output row header list, I’ll give you the exact formulas with the right column letters. Which video metrics do you want in the final sheet? (Pick: views, likes, comments count, publishedAt, channel, duration, tags) If you answer those, I’ll update the KB with: Your exact column mapping from ScrapeCreators exports A clean “one-click” Google Sheets layout (final schema + formulas) A QA checklist (missing comments, disabled comments, duplicates, reply handling) it uses youtube api. Good — if ScrapeCreators is using the official YouTube Data API, you’re in the “stable + lower-risk” lane. That also locks in one important constraint: You can’t ask the YouTube API to return comments already sorted by “most liked.” The API supports ordering by relevance (Top comments) or time (Newest). So the correct workflow is: pull a sufficiently large set of comments per video → then rank/sort by likeCount in Google Sheets. Source: YouTube Data API commentThreads.list order parameter = time or relevance. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/commentThreads/list Below is the cleanest, no-code SOP to do exactly what you want. Knowledge Base (KB) — “ScrapeCreators (YouTube API) → Comments Ranked by Likes in Google Sheets” KB v1.2 (2025-12-22) Confirmed: ScrapeCreators uses YouTube Data API (not HTML scraping). Goal: Input = Google Sheet of YouTube videos → Output = Google Sheet with (a) video metrics + (b) comments ranked by likeCount per video. Non-negotiable constraint: API cannot sort by likeCount; we sort in Sheets after extraction. Recommended data model: two exports (Comments table + Video Metrics table) joined by videoId. A) Build your INPUT Google Sheet (video list) Create a Google Sheet with a tab named: INPUT_videos Col\tHeader\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tRationale A\tvideo_url\tFull YouTube URL(s)\tSource list\tHuman-readable B\tvideo_id\tAuto-extracted\t11-char ID\tMost tools/APIs are more reliable with IDs C\tlabel\tOptional tag\tSegment tag\tHelps analysis + reporting Formula (B2) to extract video_id (works for watch, youtu.be, shorts): Copy =IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"v=([^&]+)\"), IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"youtu\\.be/([^?&]+)\"), IFERROR(REGEXEXTRACT(A2,\"shorts/([^?&]+)\"), \"\"))) B) ScrapeCreators SOP (2 runs: Comments + Video Metrics) Run 1 — Export Comments Go to ScrapeCreators → YouTube → Video → Comments (your doc link). Click-by-click setup Step\tWhat to click/do\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tData/rationale 1\tChoose Input Source = Google Sheets (or paste list / CSV if that’s what they offer)\tGoogle Sheet share link OR CSV upload\tTool loads your rows\tEnables bulk processing 2\tSelect which column to use\tvideo_id (preferred)\tScrapeCreators maps each row to a video\tReduces URL parsing errors 3\tSet Order\trelevance (Top comments)\tReturned comments skew “top”\tAPI-supported sort option (not likeCount) 4\tSet Max comments per video\te.g., 200–1000 per video\tMore rows per video\tYou need enough depth to find true most-liked 5\tInclude replies (if option exists)\tYes/No\tReply rows included or separate export\tAPI replies handling varies by implementation 6\tRun test on 1–2 videos\t1–2 IDs\tPreview rows\tConfirm likeCount + text present 7\tRun full batch\tAll IDs\tComments dataset generated\tReady for ranking in Sheets 8\tExport destination\tExport to Google Sheets\tNew tab/sheet created\tKeeps workflow no-code Must-have output fields (verify they exist): videoId (join key) commentId textDisplay or textOriginal (comment content) likeCount (ranking metric) publishedAt (optional) authorDisplayName, replyCount Source: Comment thread/comment resources include like counts and text fields. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/commentThreads Run 2 — Export Video Metrics In ScrapeCreators, run the “Video details / Video stats / Video info” endpoint (typically maps to videos.list). Click-by-click setup Step\tWhat to click/do\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tData/rationale 1\tOpen YouTube → Video → Details/Stats\tNone\tVideo details tool page\tNeeded for per-video metrics 2\tInput source\tSame Google Sheet\tTool reads video_id list\tSame join key 3\tSelect fields/parts (if configurable)\tstatistics, snippet (+ contentDetails if you want duration)\tMetrics columns included\tThese parts contain views/likes/comments, title/date, duration 4\tRun\tAll IDs\tOne row per video\tClean metrics table 5\tExport to Google Sheets\tDestination sheet\tNew metrics tab/sheet\tReady to join Source: videos.list returns statistics including view/like/comment counts. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/videos C) Google Sheets: Join + Rank “Most Liked” Comments Assume you now have: EXPORT_comments (one row per comment) EXPORT_video_metrics (one row per video) Create a new tab: FINAL_ranked_comments 1) Bring in video metrics next to each comment (XLOOKUP) Example (adjust column letters to your actual exports): Video Title (B2): Copy =XLOOKUP($A2, EXPORT_video_metrics!$A:$A, EXPORT_video_metrics!$B:$B, \"\") View Count (C2): Copy =XLOOKUP($A2, EXPORT_video_metrics!$A:$A, EXPORT_video_metrics!$C:$C, \"\") Where A2 = videoId in your final table. 2) Rank comments by likeCount within each video Assuming: videoId = column A likeCount = column E Put in G2: Copy =IF($A2=\"\",\"\",RANK.EQ($E2, FILTER($E:$E, $A:$A=$A2), 0)) Expected output: 1 = most-liked comment for that video. 3) Filter to “Top N comments per video” To get Top 10 per video, you can simply filter where rankWithinVideo <= 10. Example filter view: Copy =FILTER(FINAL_ranked_comments!A:G, FINAL_ranked_comments!G:G<=10) D) Workflow Map (so it’s easy to audit) Google Sheets: INPUT_videos ScrapeCreators Run #1: commentThreads.list via YouTube API ScrapeCreators Run #2: videos.list via YouTube API Sheet: EXPORT_comments Sheet: EXPORT_video_metrics Sheet: FINAL_ranked_comments Rank by likeCount per video + Top N views Copy E) Practical settings (what I recommend) Setting\tRecommendation\tExpected Output Impact\tWhy Comment order\trelevance\tHigher-quality “top” comments first\tMatches “Top comments” behavior (closest API option) Comments per video\tStart 300–500 (go higher for big videos)\tBetter chance true most-liked is included\tIf you only pull 50, you may miss the real winners Replies\tOnly include if needed\tMore rows + complexity\tReplies can swamp your sheet; do separately if needed F) Quotas & limits (what can break) Even via API, you can hit YouTube Data API quota (default is commonly 10,000 units/day per project, depending on your setup). If ScrapeCreators uses their API project, they handle it; if it uses your API key, you need to watch quotas. Sources: Quotas overview + method cost references. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/getting-started#quota https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/determine_quota_cost Two questions so I can lock this into a “done-for-you” sheet layout (with exact formulas tied to your column headers) In your ScrapeCreators comments export, what are the exact column names for: videoId, comment text, and like count? (Paste just the header row.) Do you want only top-level comments, or top-level + replies? Once you paste the header row, I’ll update the KB with: The exact column mapping (no guessing) A finalized Google Sheets template (tabs + formulas) that outputs Top 10 most-liked comments per video plus video metrics automatically. If I wanted to put this in an eight in automation, does it need to be in curl?No j s or python if we put this into n8n scrape crestors had code in n8n, curl and python. which do you need for n8n For n8n, you do not need cURL, JS, or Python. cURL in docs is just a demo format showing: endpoint + method + headers + body. In n8n, you replicate that using the HTTP Request node (click-by-click), no code. So: I need either (A) the n8n workflow snippet ScrapeCreators provides, or (B) the cURL snippet so I can translate it 1:1 into n8n node fields. KB (Knowledge Base) — n8n + ScrapeCreators YouTube Comments KB v1.3 (2025-12-22) Confirmed: ScrapeCreators uses YouTube API. Automation target: n8n workflow that reads a Google Sheet of YouTube videos → calls ScrapeCreators → writes comments + metrics back to Google Sheets → ranks by likeCount (either in Sheets or n8n sort). No-code constraint: no JS/Python; use n8n native nodes + expressions only. What I need for n8n (choose one) Option 1 (best): ScrapeCreators “n8n” example If ScrapeCreators provides an n8n block, send it. I can tell you exactly how to import and configure credentials. Option 2 (totally fine): ScrapeCreators cURL example If you paste the cURL command from their docs, I’ll translate it into: HTTP Request node URL Method (GET/POST) Headers (Authorization/API key) Query params / JSON body Bottom line: For n8n I “need” the same information cURL contains, but we will not run cURL. n8n Build Plan (No Code) — Click-by-click SOP This is the standard pattern to automate “Google Sheet list → API calls → Google Sheet output”. Workflow nodes (high level) Schedule Trigger (or Manual Trigger) Google Sheets: Read input rows (video URLs/IDs) Split In Batches (prevents rate limits) HTTP Request to ScrapeCreators (comments) HTTP Request to ScrapeCreators (video metrics) (optional second call or second workflow) Google Sheets: Append rows to output tabs Ranking done in Google Sheets (recommended) or in n8n via Item Lists sort Detailed SOP Table (what you click + expected input/output) Step\tIn n8n (click-by-click)\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tRationale / notes 1\tCreate new workflow → add Schedule Trigger\tSchedule (e.g., daily 6am)\tWorkflow runs automatically\tAutomation 2\tAdd Google Sheets node → “Read” / “Get Many”\tSpreadsheet ID + Sheet tab INPUT_videos\tItems: one per row with video_id\tPull your URL list 3\tAdd Split In Batches node\tBatch size (e.g., 10)\tOnly 10 videos processed at a time\tPrevent quota/rate issues 4\tAdd HTTP Request node (ScrapeCreators Comments endpoint)\tURL, method, headers, body/params from ScrapeCreators docs\tJSON response containing comments + likeCount + videoId\tCore extraction 5\t(If needed) Add HTTP Request node (Video metrics endpoint)\tSame videoId\tJSON response with viewCount/likeCount/commentCount/title\tPull metrics separately if comments response doesn’t include stats 6\tAdd Set node to map fields into flat columns\tField mappings (no code)\tClean item fields matching sheet columns\tSheets likes flat rows 7\tAdd Google Sheets node → Append to EXPORT_comments\tMapped fields\tNew rows added\tPersistent storage 8\tAdd Google Sheets node → Append to EXPORT_video_metrics\tMapped metrics\tOne row per video\tJoin key videoId 9\tIn Google Sheets, create FINAL_ranked_comments formulas (rank by likeCount)\tlikeCount + videoId columns\tRanked comments per video\tRanking is easiest in Sheets Do you need cURL specifically for n8n? No. But if ScrapeCreators only gives examples in cURL/Python, paste the cURL and I’ll convert it to n8n fields. What I need from the cURL snippet Endpoint URL Method (GET/POST) Headers (Authorization / API key) Query params or JSON body Pagination fields (e.g., nextPageToken) if present Ranking “Most Liked” without code (best practice) Because API ordering is relevance or time, you should: Pull enough comments per video (e.g., 300–500) Rank in Google Sheets by likeCount That avoids writing any JS in n8n. Workflow Diagram (so you can sanity-check it) Schedule Trigger Google Sheets: Read INPUT_videos Split In Batches HTTP Request: ScrapeCreators Comments HTTP Request: ScrapeCreators Video Metrics Set: Map comment fields Set: Map metrics fields Google Sheets: Append EXPORT_comments Google Sheets: Append EXPORT_video_metrics Sheets formulas: rank by likeCount Copy Quick question (so I can give you the exact node-by-node configuration) Paste the ScrapeCreators cURL example from the comments docs (and metrics docs if separate). I’ll return a complete n8n SOP with: Exact HTTP Request node settings (URL, headers, body) Exact Google Sheets node mappings A ready-to-import n8n workflow structure (no JS/Python) would it be better ti use https://brightdata.com/products/web-scraper?pscd=get.brightdata.com&ps_partner_key=MTgwODIzNDM4ZTJl&ps_xid=ddqsY59sX6XPwj&gsxid=ddqsY59sX6XPwj&gspk=MTgwODIzNDM4ZTJl&utm_source=affiliates&utm_campaign=MTgwODIzNDM4ZTJl If your goal is YouTube comments + video metrics into Google Sheets, and you’ve already confirmed ScrapeCreators uses the YouTube Data API, then in most cases ScrapeCreators is the better choice than Bright Data’s Web Scraper—because it’s more compliant, more stable, and usually simpler to automate in n8n. Bright Data becomes “better” only when you specifically need things the API/tool can’t reliably deliver (scale, coverage, freshness, or non-API fields), and you’re comfortable with the higher compliance/fragility risk of web scraping YouTube pages. KB (Knowledge Base) Update — “ScrapeCreators vs Bright Data for YouTube Comments” KB v1.4 (2025-12-22) Decision: Prefer API-based extraction (ScrapeCreators) unless requirements force scraping. Key constraint: YouTube API does not support sorting comments by “most liked” directly; must rank by likeCount after export. Source: commentThreads.list order = time or relevance. https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/commentThreads/list Risk note: Web scraping YouTube may violate YouTube Terms (accessing content by unauthorized means). https://www.youtube.com/t/terms 1) Decision Matrix (what’s “better” depends on your constraints) Criteria\tScrapeCreators (YouTube API)\tBright Data Web Scraper (scraping)\tMy take Compliance / account risk\tGenerally safer (official API path)\tHigher risk (scraping YouTube HTML)\tAPI wins Stability over time\tStable schemas + known limits\tCan break when YouTube UI changes\tAPI wins Setup for n8n\tStraightforward HTTP calls\tAlso doable, but often more moving parts (collectors, scraping browser, etc.)\tAPI wins “Most liked comments” ranking\tMust rank in Sheets (post-process)\tStill likely post-process; scraping doesn’t magically solve ranking unless you only scrape “Top comments” view\tTie (post-process anyway) Scale\tLimited by API quotas + tool limits\tCan scale via scraping infrastructure\tBright Data can win at very large scale Completeness\tAPI returns what API returns\tScrape can sometimes capture what’s rendered (but not guaranteed)\tDepends on use case Cost predictability\tUsually more predictable\tCan get expensive at scale (bandwidth/compute/proxy)\tUsually API wins early Verdict for your stated use case: Stick with ScrapeCreators (API) unless you hit a hard wall (quota/coverage). 2) The two “hard walls” that justify Bright Data Use Bright Data only if one of these is true: You need far more volume than the API/quota/tool can handle (e.g., thousands of videos × thousands of comments each on a schedule), and you can’t get higher API quota / additional projects. You need data not available/consistent via API/tool (rare for basic “comments + likeCount + video stats,” which the API supports well). 3) Facts that matter (so you don’t buy the wrong solution) Fact A — API cannot sort by “most liked” You can request: order=relevance (Top comments-ish) order=time (Newest) You cannot request order=likeCount. So you must extract and sort yourself. Source: https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/docs/commentThreads/list Fact B — Scraping YouTube may violate Terms YouTube’s Terms restrict accessing the service via unauthorized means (scraping is commonly considered unauthorized unless explicitly permitted). Source: https://www.youtube.com/t/terms (Also relevant: YouTube API Terms if you use the API: https://developers.google.com/youtube/terms/api-services-terms-of-service) 4) Best-practice architecture (n8n + Google Sheets) — no code required Regardless of provider, the clean pattern is: Google Sheets: INPUT_videos n8n: Read rows Split in Batches Fetch comments Fetch video metrics Append to EXPORT_comments Append to EXPORT_video_metrics Google Sheets: Rank by likeCount + Top N views Copy Important: Do ranking in Google Sheets (formulas) rather than n8n code. 5) Implementation SOP (choose your path) Path 1 (Recommended): ScrapeCreators (YouTube API) → n8n → Google Sheets Step\tClick-by-click\tExpected Input\tExpected Output 1\tIn Google Sheets create INPUT_videos tab with video_url, video_id\tYouTube URLs\tClean video_id column 2\tIn n8n add Google Sheets node → Read\tSpreadsheet + tab name\tItems list of video IDs 3\tAdd Split In Batches\tBatch size (e.g., 10)\tContro"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"[Content truncated — view full chat at source URL]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=e3f431c5-2d56-4022-bc19-008cd9031555","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=e3f431c5-2d56-4022-bc19-008cd9031555"}]}]}]
